    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e072905a33248bc2",
      "text": "This pure formal commonality in the intellectual field, which encompasses all stages of commodity production and is unchanging in itself, has an equally formal correlate in the economic field, which is emphasized by Marx, among others, in the following way: »Whatever the sequence of periodic reproductions and previous accumulations that the capital functioning today has gone through, it always preserves its original virginity. As long as the laws of exchange are respected in each act of exchange, the mode of appropriation [of surplus labor] can undergo a total revolution without touching in any way the right of property proper to commodity production. This same right is in force, as it was in the beginning, when the product belonged to the producer, and when the latter, exchanging equivalent for equivalent, could enrich himself only through his own labor, so also in the capitalist period, when the social wealth becomes, to an ever-increasing degree, the property of those who are able to appropriate ever anew the unpaid labor of others.«"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "de367b26fd521808",
      "text": "»This result becomes inevitable as soon as labor power is freely sold as a commodity by the worker himself. But only then does commodity production become generalized and become a typical form of production; only then is every product produced from the outset for sale, and all produced wealth passes through circulation [and commodity abstraction – S. R.]. Only there, where wage-labor has its basis, does commodity production force itself upon the whole of society; but only there, too, does it unfold all its hidden potencies.« (MEWBd. 23, p. 613.)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1ae3687d0748ff1d",
      "text": "This significant passage in Marx must be kept in mind throughout the following explanations, because it identifies anew the form constant that pervades commodity production in all modes of development »taken individually in every act of exchange«. It is the form constant that is peculiar to the fetish character of the commodity and the reification mechanism of exchange, and which Marx elsewhere also calls the »elementary form of the commodity« and the »germ of the money form« or also »the eternal laws of commodity exchange« (208)."
