      "type": "edit",
      "id": "b54ffc111f45fb96",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "b54ffc111f45fb96",
        "text": "\"Intellect\" is a fetish term for mental activity, which is essentially divorced from manual labor. Intellect is always to be seen in the historical relation to manual labor, certain forms of intellect to certain forms of manual labor. Whether intellectual labor occurs or not, of what kind and with what concepts of cognition, depends on the historically given conditions of physical production activity, that is, on the state of development of the productive forces and the forms of labor processes determined thereby, as well as on the social relations of production. We therefore do not speak of >>intellect<< in the meaning of a brain faculty specifically implanted in man and also not in the meaning of a mental faculty of man to mirror his outside and environment, i.e. not at all in the epistemological meaning of an underlying subject-object relation. We understand >>intellect<< rather as a phenomenon of a conceptual mode of thinking and cognition, which is linked to very specific economic social formations and can be precisely explained from them, indeed can be derived from them, and in which the manual workers do not participate because their activity does not provide them with access to it. The fact that the social causes of this division appear to the manual workers for the most part as natural facts does not change the matter. Only in a Marxist analysis do the reasons for the divorce of headwork and manual labor become recognizable as socially conditioned and therefore also in their essence as socially changeable and abolishable. The historical materialist explanation of the divorce of mental and physical labor is therefore a critical task of immediate practical-political importance."
      },
